<pre>
JSON stands for JavaScript Object Notation
JSON is a lightweight data-interchange format
JSON is language independent *
JSON is "self-describing" and easy to understand
</pre>

<h1 id="jsonä¸xmlçš„æ¯”è¾ƒ">JSONä¸XMLçš„æ¯”è¾ƒ</h1>
<h2 id="ç›¸åŒç‚¹">ç›¸åŒç‚¹</h2>
<pre>
 Much Like XML Because
Both JSON and XML is "self describing" (human readable)
Both JSON and XML is hierarchical (values within values)
Both JSON and XML can be parsed and used by lots of programming languages
Both JSON and XML can be fetched with an XMLHttpRequest
</pre>

<h2 id="ä¸åŒç‚¹">ä¸åŒç‚¹</h2>
<pre>
Much Unlike XML Because
JSON doesn't use end tag
JSON is shorter
JSON is quicker to read and write
JSON can use arrays
The biggest difference is:

 XML has to be parsed with an XML parser, JSON can be parsed by a standard JavaScript function.
</pre>

<h1 id="ä¸ºä»€ä¹ˆä½¿ç”¨json">ä¸ºä»€ä¹ˆä½¿ç”¨JSON</h1>
<pre>

A common use of JSON is to read data from a web server, and display the data in a web page.

For AJAX applications, JSON is faster and easier than XML:

Using XML

Fetch an XML document
Use the XML DOM to loop through the document
Extract values and store in variables


Using JSON

Fetch a JSON string
JSON.Parse the JSON string

</pre>

